+{"type":"message","id":"e1f67b13","parentId":"bc65ac14","timestamp":"2026-03-24T06:04:33.506Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Plan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Build the Weekly Commit Module v1 — a production micro-frontend (TypeScript/React) with Java 21 modular-monolith backend replacing 15Five for weekly planning. Implements structured weekly commitments with RCDO strategy linkage, chess-layer prioritization, lock/reconcile lifecycle with immutable snapshots, explicit carry-forward with provenance, native tickets with status workflow, manager team dashboard with exception review, conservative explainable AI assistance, rules-based notifications, derived read models for reporting, and comprehensive audit logging. Delivered as a route-level Module Federation remote integrated into the PA host app. Note: The PRD recommends Java 21 (§22) and all checks are npm-based; the monorepo root package.json orchestrates both the TypeScript frontend (Vite/React) and Java backend (Gradle) via shell-out scripts. SQL migrations use Flyway against PostgreSQL.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 20,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Monorepo scaffolding and build infrastructure\",\n    \"2. Domain model types, enums, and database schema\",\n    \"3. RCDO hierarchy management API\",\n    \"4. Weekly plan creation and commit CRUD API\",\n    \"5. Lock lifecycle and baseline snapshot API\",\n    \"6. Post-lock scope change and reconciliation API\",\n    \"7. Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\",\n    \"8. Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\",\n    \"9. Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\",\n    \"10. RCDO management UI\",\n    \"11. My Week page with commit list and capacity meter\",\n    \"12. Lock flow and reconcile view UI\",\n    \"13. Team Week dashboard UI\",\n    \"14. Tickets UI and search/filter/history views\",\n    \"15. Notifications backend and frontend panel\",\n    \"16. AI provider abstraction and commit assistance\",\n    \"17. AI risk detection and reconciliation assistance\",\n    \"18. Derived read models and operational reporting\",\n    \"19. Configuration management and admin settings\",\n    \"20. Audit logging, accessibility, and integration polish\"\n  ]\n}\n\nStep 7: Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-7\",\n  \"title\": \"Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\",\n  \"description\": \"Implement carry-forward (PRD §13 FR-6) and native ticket model (PRD §14).\\n\\n**CarryForwardService:**\\n- `carryForward(sourceCommitId, targetWeekStart, reason, reasonText?)`: creates a new commit in the target week's plan with provenance link to source. Copies title, description, chess piece, RCDO link, estimate. Sets `carryForwardSourceId`, increments `carryForwardStreak` (source streak + 1). New commit inserted at bottom of target plan's priority order.\\n- If target week plan doesn't exist, lazily create it.\\n- If target week plan is already LOCKED, add the carry-forward commit as a post-lock scope change event (COMMIT_ADDED with carry-forward reason).\\n- `CarryForwardLink` record: sourceCommitId, targetCommitId, reason, reasonText, createdAt.\\n- Carry-forward reason from controlled enum list plus optional free text.\\n- `getCarryForwardLineage(commitId)`: returns full chain of carry-forward ancestry.\\n\\n**TicketService (WorkItemService):**\\n- CRUD: create, read, update, delete tickets.\\n- Fields: key/id (auto-generated), title, description, status, assignee, reporter, team, priority, optional estimate points, optional RCDO link, optional target week.\\n- Status workflow: BACKLOG → READY → IN_PROGRESS → BLOCKED → DONE → CANCELED. Validate transitions are legal.\\n- `WorkItemStatusHistory`: every status change timestamped and stored for duration-in-status reporting.\\n- Commit-ticket linking: a commit may link to zero or one ticket. In the same week, prevent the same assignee from linking the same ticket to multiple active commits.\\n- RCDO defaulting: when linking ticket to commit, if commit has no RCDO, default from ticket. If both have RCDO and they differ, flag a warning.\\n\\n**REST endpoints:**\\n- `POST /api/plans/{id}/commits/{commitId}/carry-forward` — carry forward a commit\\n- `GET /api/commits/{id}/lineage` — carry-forward lineage\\n- `GET/POST/PUT/DELETE /api/tickets` — ticket CRUD\\n- `GET /api/tickets/{id}/history` — status history\\n- `PUT /api/plans/{id}/commits/{commitId}/link-ticket` — link ticket to commit\\n\\n**Unit tests:** carry-forward creates new commit with provenance, streak incrementing, carry-forward into locked week, lineage chain traversal, ticket status transitions (valid and invalid), status history recording, same-week duplicate link prevention, RCDO defaulting and mismatch warning.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nThis is relay round 2. Another agent has already worked on this step.\n\nYou are in VERIFICATION MODE. Your default action is to APPROVE.\nFocus your review on the DIFF — the changes made in the previous round.\nOnly make changes if there is a MATERIAL defect: failing check, missing step requirement, logic bug, or security issue.\nStyle preferences, alternative approaches, comment wording, and optional polish are NOT grounds for changes.\n\nIf all checks pass and the step requirements are met, approve immediately.\nLog anything else you notice as observations — do not act on them.\n\nPrevious agent's notes:\nHere is a complete summary of what was implemented in this step:\n\n---\n\n## What was implemented\n\n### CarryForwardService (`carryforward/service/`)\n- **`carryForward(sourceCommitId, targetWeekStart, reason, reasonText, actorUserId)`**: Copies title, description, chess piece, RCDO, estimate and success criteria into a new commit in the target week's plan. Sets `carryForwardSourceId` and increments `carryForwardStreak` (source + 1). New commit placed at bottom priority order. Lazily creates the target plan if missing. If target plan is LOCKED, records a `COMMIT_ADDED` scope-change event (prefixed `CARRY_FORWARD:reason`).\n- **`getCarryForwardLineage(commitId)`**: Traverses ancestors (upward via `carryForwardSourceId`) and descendants (downward via `CarryForwardLinkRepository`) and returns the full chain ordered oldest-first.\n\n### TicketService (`ticket/service/TicketService`)\n- Full CRUD: create (with auto-generated `T-N` key), read, update (partial), delete.\n- **Status workflow**: enforced via a static transition map — BACKLOG → READY/IN_PROGRESS/CANCELED, READY → IN_PROGRESS/BACKLOG/CANCELED, IN_PROGRESS → DONE/BLOCKED/READY/CANCELED, BLOCKED → IN_PROGRESS/CANCELED, DONE/CANCELED are terminals.\n- Every status change appends a `WorkItemStatusHistory` entry (with `fromStatus`, `toStatus`, `changedByUserId`).\n- Idempotent: same-status transition returns immediately without recording history.\n\n### LinkTicketService (`ticket/service/LinkTicketService`)\n- Links a work item to a commit on a DRAFT plan.\n- **Duplicate prevention**: checks for other active (non-CANCELED) commits by the same owner linked to the same ticket in the same week.\n- **RCDO defaulting**: if commit has no RCDO and ticket has one, the commit inherits it. If both differ, returns a warning message without blocking.\n\n### REST Endpoints\n- `POST /api/plans/{planId}/commits/{commitId}/carry-forward` — carry forward a commit\n- `GET /api/commits/{commitId}/lineage` — carry-forward lineage\n- `GET /api/tickets?teamId=…` — list tickets by team\n- `POST /api/tickets` — create ticket\n- `GET /api/tickets/{id}` — get ticket\n- `PUT /api/tickets/{id}` — update ticket\n- `DELETE /api/tickets/{id}` — delete ticket\n- `PUT /api/tickets/{id}/status` — transition status\n- `GET /api/tickets/{id}/history` — status history\n- `PUT /api/plans/{planId}/commits/{commitId}/link-ticket` — link ticket to commit\n\n### Updated Repositories\n- `WorkItemStatusHistoryRepository`: added `findByWorkItemIdOrderByCreatedAtAsc`\n- `WorkItemRepository`: added `findByTeamId`, `countByTeamId`\n- `WeeklyCommitRepository`: added `findActiveCommitsForTicketByOwnerExcluding` JPQL query\n\n### Unit Tests (36 total)\n- `CarryForwardServiceTest` (11 tests): provenance creation, streak incrementing, lazy plan creation, carry-forward into locked plan, lineage traversal (2-generation chain), error cases\n- `TicketServiceTest` (16 tests): create with auto-key, invalid estimates, all valid and invalid status transitions, history recording, idempotent same-status, delete\n- `LinkTicketServiceTest` (9 tests): happy path, RCDO defaulting (3 cases: no RCDO, same RCDO, mismatch warning), duplicate-link prevention, state guard (locked plan), error cases\n\nVerdict: changes_made\n\n```observations\n- [low] backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket/service/TicketService.java: The auto-key generator (T-N) uses `countByTeamId` which races under concurrent creates — two concurrent creates for the same team could generate duplicate keys. The DB unique constraint on `(team_id, key)` will catch this at the DB level and surface as a DataIntegrityViolationException, but the caller receives a 500 rather than a meaningful 409. A retry or DB sequence could solve this in a future step.\n- [low] backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward/service/CarryForwardService.java: The `recordCarryForwardScopeChangeEvent` method hand-crafts a minimal JSON payload rather than using ObjectMapper, which is slightly fragile (e.g., special chars in commit title). Using ObjectMapper (already used in ScopeChangeService) would be more robust. Not a bug since the title is user-supplied text unlikely to contain raw JSON metacharacters in practice.\n```\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n\nFiles changed so far:\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/cost.json\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/observations.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/sessions/continuous/relay-a/2026-03-24T04-23-35-130Z_4c4202d2-9023-459a-b908-dfaede19919d.jsonl\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/state.json\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WeeklyCommitRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WorkItemRepository.java\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/domain/repository/WorkItemStatusHistoryRepository.java\n.pi/duet/runs/2026-03-24T03-49-04-151Z-dd75a832/steps/7\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward\nbackend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/carryforward\nbackend/src/test/java/com/weeklycommit/ticket\n\nWhen done, explain what you reviewed, what you changed (if anything), and your assessment.\n\nEnd with:\nVerdict: approve  — if the step is complete and correct, no more changes needed\nVerdict: changes_made  — if you made fixes or improvements\nVerdict: replan_needed  — if the step is structurally impossible to complete as planned and needs controller-managed replanning"}],"timestamp":1774332273506}}
